@NODE "Introduction" "bdAnim Introduction"

@{B}    Introduction@{UB}

    BackDropAnim is a simple animationplayer, that plays a 'busy-' or 'transfer-'
animation on screen. It's primary use is to make the workbench a little more
nice-looking, but it can also be useful due to it's usermenu-function and arexx
functions (arexx-interface is quite limited at the moment).

I got the idea for this program from 'WBAnim' by Gaz/Dalnet a while ago. The problem
with WBAnim was that it didn't do any recalculation of the animation colours,
and thus looked pretty bad on my cybergraphics screen. This version works, as
far as I've tested, fine on both aga and graphicboard displays, using data-
types to load the animations..

I also wanted a little more functionality of the program, so I added functions
to start, stop and change speed via @{"Arexx" link Arexx}, the possibility to launch scripts or
programs via a @{"usermenu" link Menues} and some @{"tooltypes" link ToolTypes} to make the client more configurable.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Requirements" "Requirements"

@{B}    Requirements@{UB}

    To use this program you need

    ° MUI, Magical User Interface by Stefan Stuntz. Availible on Aminet.

    ° TransferAnim.mcc, From version 2 bdAnim makes use of TransferAnim.mcc for
      displaying it's animations. It is however included in the archive.

    ° Datatypes, The program uses datatypes to load graphics, thus at least 3.0
      is required.

    I think that's it.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Installation" "Installation"

@{B}    Installation@{UB}

    The program is easy to install, just 

    ° Copy mui/TransferAnim.mc? to mui:libs/mui/

    ° Copy the 'bdAnim' and 'bdAnim.info' to the place you want it.

    ° If you want the about-window animations to show up, you also need a drawer
      'anims' in the same directory, containing the supplied files 'about' and
      'aboutlogo'.

    ° I suggest you put your own animations in this drawer too, although they
      can be placed anywhere, since the path and name is specified via @{"ToolTypes" link ToolTypes}.

    ° If you want the animation to show up everytime you boot, just put bdAnim or
      a project icon linking to bdAnim in the WBStartup drawer.

    ° If you want to use the arexx scripts, copy them to your rexx: drawer.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Usage" "Usage"

@{B}    Usage@{UB}

    The program is very simple to use.
When you first unpack it, all you have to do is to launch one of it's icons.
To make it fit your personal preferences better, you might want to change
the configutration.

These are your options:

    ° @{"Animations" link Animations} Make your own animations to use with 
      bdAnim.

    ° @{"ToolTypes" link ToolTypes}, use Tooltypes to conifgure what animation
      to use, where to place it, speed, usermenues, etc.
    
    ° @{"Arexx" link Arexx}, use the Arexx inteface to control your animation.

    ° @{"User Menues" link Menues}, Set up you own menues to launch programs
      and scripts.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Animations" "Usage/Animations"

@{B}    Animations@{UB}

The animations are quite simple to create. Just like transferanimations for your
browser, the frames are put side by side in one wide image.

Any transferanimation from aminet should be possible to use.

If you do not specify the width of your animations with the correct @{"ToolType" link ToolTypes},
the program will assume that each frame is as wide as the image is high. 

The first image (the leftmost one) may or may not be a part of the animation. See
the @{"Skipfirst" link ToolTypes} tooltype.

If you still don't have a clue of how to make your own animations, just look at
the one's coming with the program in you favorite image-viewer, and you'll clearly
see how they are built up. 

@ENDNODE
@NODE "ToolTypes" "Usage/ToolTypes"

@{B}    ToolTypes@{UB}

There are at the moment a few tooltypes to help you configure your animations.

    ° 'anim=<path/file>' specifies what animationfile to use.
      The animation image can be of any imageformat you have a datatype for.
      (Only images at the moment, though)

      Example: 'anim=anims/boing.jpg'

    ° 'width=<w>' specifies the width of each frame in the image. This tooltype is not
      needed if each frame is as wide as its height (you have a square anim).

      Example: 'width=64'

    ° 'height=<h>' can be used to cut of the lower part of the animation. 

      Example: 'height=12'

    ° 'top=<y>' specifies on what vertical position the animation will be positioned.
      A positive integer specifies pixelposition.
      A value of -1 means in the middle of the screen.
      A value of -2 positions the animation at the (vertical) position the mouse
         is held
      A value of -3 positions it just below the titlebar, and -4 to -9 positions
         1 to 6 pixels below the titlebar.
      Note that this tooltype don't work if your animation is 'snaphot'ed

      Example: 'top=-3'

    ° 'left=<x>' is the same as 'top' for horizontal positioning. 
      A positive integer specifies the pixelposition.
      A value of -1 puts it on the middle of the screen.
      A valude of -2 positions it wherever the mouse is (horizontaly).
      Note that this tooltype don't work if your animation is 'snaphot'ed

      Example: 'left=-1'

    ° 'backdrop' makes the animation window a backdrop one.
      If this is not specified, other windows can fall behind the animation.
      For some reason, it seems that the window will fall behind the titlebar
      if its 'backdrop' on some systems (cgfx??)

      Example: 'backdrop'

    ° 'fps=<fps>' specifies in how many frames per second the animation should be
      shown. 24 fps is usually a good choice.

      Example: 'fps=24'

    ° 'millis=<millis>', an alternative way of setting the speed of the animation.
      This speciefies how many milliseconds are to pass between each frame.

      Example: 'millis=41'  (24 frames a sec)
               'millis=5000' (5 seconds between each frame)

    ° 'rexx=<name>' specifies the name of the arexx port. If this is not chosen, the
      port will have the name 'bdAnim.x' where x is the number of bdAnim started.
      If you chose something else, the '.x' will still be added to the portname.
      The name of the port is visible in the 'about' window'.

      Example: 'rexx=AMIGA' (would give the arexxport 'AMIGA.1' the first time
                                     the program is launched)

    ° 'skipfirst' makes the animation skip the first frame while playing, and
      only showing it if the animation is paused. Many transferanims are made this
      way, with a separated first frame.
      The first frame will be the one shown when paused, if this tooltype is
      there or not.

      Example: 'skipfirst'

    ° 'hide' makes the animationwindow iconified when the animation is stopped.
      The hiding method can be chosen in the MUI prefs, either appicon, appmenu
      or nothing (probably looks best).

      Example: 'hide'

    ° 'noloop' turns off animation looping. If you want to control your animation
      from arexx, and only want it to play once, this is good.

      Example: 'noloop'

    ° 'Delay=<millis>' Tells the animationplayer to pause the animation <millis>
      milliseconds before looping. If 'hide' and 'noloop' is chosen, it waits
      <millis> seconds before hiding.

      Example: 'Delay=1000' (for a one second wait)

    ° 'sync=<port>' Will make the program send a sync command to the arexx port
      <port>, which should be another bdAnim arexx-port. This function will make
      it possible to have i e shadows synchronized with it's object etc.

    ° 'syncstop' When synchronization is used, this will also sync the stop of the
      anims. So if the slave anim have been delayed by some reason, it will still
      stop when it's master will.

    ° 'MenuTitle' and 'MenuX', see the @{"UserMenues" link Menues} section.
      They are there to set up the user menues.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Arexx" "Usage/Arexx"

@{B}    Arexx@{UB}

    At the moment, the arexx interface is very limited, but seriously, I can't
think of many functions to add. Suggestions are @{"welcome" link Author}!

    ° 'start' (no args) starts the animation once it's paused.

    ° 'stop' or 'pause' (no args) pauses the animation.

    ° 'fps' (FPS/N) sets the frames per second to 'FPS'.

    ° 'setframe' (FRAME/N) set the current frame of the animation.

    ° 'sync' will restart the animation from frame 0. (and start playing if earlier
      paused)

    ° 'quit' kills the animation app.

    ° 'hide' iconifies the animation window. Iconify method can be altered in
      the MUI prefs.

A few example scripts can be found in the 'rexx' drawer.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Menues" "Usage/User Menues"

@{B}    User Menues@{UB}

    The user menues shows up if you press the right mousebutton over the animtion-
window when the window is activated. 

You can easily put up your own menues to launch programs or scripts by the use of
tooltypes.

The title of the menu is with the 'MenuTitle' tooltype, for example

'MenuTitle=Scripts'

The menu items are set up with the 'MenuX' tooltypes, where 'X' is an integer
going from 1 to the number of menues. 

'Menu1=Start|sys:rexxc/rx astart %s'
'Menu2=Stop|sys:rexxc/rx astop %s'
'Menu3=
'Menu4=Slow|sys:rexxc/rx afps %s 12'

The part of the tooltype left of the '|' will be the name of the menuitem.
The right part will be the command executed.
The '%s' will be translated to the name of the arexx-port of animation.

The example menues above would look like:

Scripts
-------
Start
Stop
-------
Slow

And they would execute the arexx scripts 'astart port', 'astop port' and 
'afps port 12' respectively.
As you see, the empty menu, number 3, turns out as a barlabel (or separator),
this is also true for items that contains no label or command.

If the command to execute is not valid, nothing dangerous will happen.
The command is executed with a 
'run <nil: >nil: COMMAND >con:' where 'COMMAND' is your command. 
(if this means nothing to you, never mind)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "NMenues" "Usage/Menues"

@{B}    Menues@{UB}

    The menues are few and simple:

    
    Backdrop Anim:
    ° 'About' shows some information about the program.

    ° 'About MUI' shows information about MUI.

    ° 'Quit', guess what?? It quits the application.


    Settings:
    ° Position, when this menu is checked, you  can drag
      the window around with the mouse.

    ° Un/Snapshot, this choices saves and forgets the
      position of your animationwindow.
      When the window is snapshot:ed, the top and left
      tooltypes are ignored.

    ° 'MUI Prefs' brings up the MUI preferences window.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Bugs" "Bugs"

@{B}    Bugs@{UB}

    There is no known bugs at the moment, but @{U}please@{UU} report
bugs to me! Contact info is at the @{"Author" link Author} page.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Todo" "Todo"

@{B}    Todo@{UB}

    There are a few things I could add if there is a request:

    ° Play random animation. The program choses a random animation from
      a directory instead of always playing the same one.

    ° Use animation.datatype as well. I don't really feel like imple-
      menting this, but if there is a big demand, then maybe.

    ° Posibility to have a separate still image. This is already possible by
      having the chosen image as the first frame and using the 'skipfirst'
      @{"Tooltype" link ToolTypes}.

    ° A separate preferences program to make configuration more easy.

    ° Let one bdAnim app control several animations, instead of starting one
      program for each anim.

    ° A possibility not to use datatypes for pre 3.0 users. This is now a matter
      of wether TransferAnim.mcc supports pre 3.0...

    ° Possibility to have scripts executed when the animation is clicked,
      double-, middle- and rightclicked.

    ° Option to chose weather frame 1, the first frame or the last frame should
      be displayd while @{"delaying." link ToolTypes}

    Note that I probably wont implement anything of these options unless
users request them. So if you want one of these, or any other function,
drop me a @{"line" link Author}!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "History" "History"

@{B}    History@{UB}

    ° Version 2.0.
        Changed to  use TransferAnim.mcc for loading/displaying of the animations.

        Added 'Millis' tooltype for animations that play slower than one frame a second.        

        Added option to snap and unsnaphot the window position as well as the possibility
        to move the window around. This makes the top and left tooltypes kind of obsolete,
        but they still work as long as the window is not snapshotted.

    ° Fixed bug that occured when subclassing of TransferAnim.mcc was not possible.
      (This existed even before I used TransferAnim.mcc, but then I subclassed Area,
      which is quite unlikely to fail)
        

    ° Version 1.15b.
        Recompilation due to a 'might have been' bug.

    ° Version 1.15.
        Fixed CyberGuard hits from About-window, sync-function and unspecified
        animation file.
        Fixed to work with both 'tool' and 'projects' icontype. I thought this was
        already the case.

    ° Version 1.1.
        Added 'sync' tooltype and 'setframe' arexx command.
        The .mcc is developing fine, most of the code is made.

    ° Version 1.0, third public and first non beta.
        Files not being unlocked bug fixed.
        Started making a public distributable customclass (.mcc) of my class.

    ° Version 0.9ß, second public.
        Added the 'noloop' and 'delay' tooltypes.

    ° Version 0.8ß, first public version.

@ENDNODE
